narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments: I developed a core foundation of playing in an ensemble and Javanese culture.
I learned about the cultural significance of Javanese wayang kulit, was exposed to the aesthetic structures of the art and music, and learned how to place pieces that accompany wayang.
I learned about the art of Indonesian puppetry and music. Learned how to play it, to recognize aspects of the wayang, etc

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments: this class oddly fetishized Indonesian culture without learning anything about Indonesia? Its a massive gut and super easy but I wish I learned more about the culture

The subject matter of this course is so rich, it was a treat to get to watch videos of wayang and play gamelan every week. Phil is super chill, knowledgeable, and is a really good musician, it's been a great experience playing with him. I wish this class met twice a week because it's easy to forget things in between classes, which can make progress (especially at the beginning) difficult.
The assignments at times felt like busy work. Also Phils expectation for work was at times unclear

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: no it honestly just feels like a really low effort course by the department. You do almost nothing and learn almost nothing. I guess take it if you want to do 0 work. I wish we had more thoughtful assignments and learned more about Indonesian culture than the components of the wayang
It's cool. You learn to play an instrument and learn about the culture.
I would recommend this course to another student
Definitely! It was a lot of fun and doesn't add stress to your schedule, it's just a great opportunity to get to learn about and participate in a beautiful art form.
Maybe. Its an interesting vibe simply due to the others taking the class usually (a lot of student athletes)
